# Auto-Commit Workflow

After completing a major update OR a meaningful set of minor changes, proactively commit and push to the remote repository **without waiting to be asked**.

## When to Commit

- After any single major feature, refactor, or bug fix
- After a group of smaller changes that together form a logical unit
- After finishing a task or subtask from the user's request

## Commit Process

1. Run `git status` and `git diff` to review all changes
2. Run `git log -5 --oneline` to match the repo's existing commit style
3. Stage relevant files with `git add`
4. Write a concise, descriptive commit message following the repo's style
5. **Update `CHANGELOG.md`** — Before committing, update the changelog file at the repo root (`/Users/lauravanessa/Desktop/Vibecoding/Unio b2b/CHANGELOG.md`):
   - Move the pending items from the `[Sin commitear]` section into a new dated section with the commit hash and today's date (format: `DD Mmm YYYY`)
   - Reset the `[Sin commitear]` section to empty (keep the header)
   - Stage `CHANGELOG.md` along with the other files
6. Commit using a HEREDOC to preserve formatting
7. Push to the remote with `git push`

## Changelog Location

The changelog lives at `CHANGELOG.md` in the repo root. It is the single source of truth for what has changed and when. Always keep it in sync with every commit.

## Commit Message Guidelines

- Use imperative mood: "Add login form" not "Added login form"
- Be specific about what changed and why (not just what)
- Keep subject line under 72 characters
- If needed, add a short body after a blank line

## Safety Rules

- NEVER force push unless the user explicitly requests it
- NEVER skip hooks (--no-verify)
- NEVER amend a commit that has already been pushed
- If no remote is configured, inform the user and commit locally only
